result <- nn(
  bbb,
  rvar = "buyer",
  evar = c(
    "gender", "last", "total", "child", "youth", "cook", "do_it",
    "reference", "art", "geog"
  ),
  lev = "yes",
  size = 1,
  decay = 0.5,
  seed = 1234,
  data_filter = "training == 1"
)

Neural Networks as a universal approximator

Simulate data

simdat <- simulater(
  grid = "x 0 6.5 0.001",
  form = "y = x * cos(pi * x)",
  seed = 1234
)
register("simdat")
summary(simdat, dec = 4)

A plot of the simulated data

visualize(
  simdat,
  xvar = "x",
  yvar = "y",
  type = "line",
  custom = FALSE
)

Estimating NNs with different number of nodes in the hidden layer

plot_list <- list()
plot_list$nn2 <- nn(
  simdat,
  rvar = "y",
  evar = "x",
  type = "regression",
  size = 2,
  decay = 0,
  seed = 1234
) %>%
  predict(pred_data = simdat) %>%
  visualize(
    xvar = "x", yvar = "Prediction", type = "line", 
    labs = list(title = "2 nodes in the hidden layer"),
    custom = TRUE
  )

plot_list$nn3 <- nn(
  simdat,
  rvar = "y",
  evar = "x",
  type = "regression",
  size = 3,
  decay = 0,
  seed = 1234
) %>%
  predict(pred_data = simdat) %>%
  visualize(
    xvar = "x", yvar = "Prediction", type = "line", 
    labs = list(title = "3 nodes in the hidden layer"),
    custom = TRUE
  )

plot_list$nn4 <- nn(
  simdat,
  rvar = "y",
  evar = "x",
  type = "regression",
  size = 4,
  decay = 0,
  seed = 1234
) %>%
  predict(pred_data = simdat) %>%
  visualize(
    xvar = "x", yvar = "Prediction", type = "line", 
    labs = list(title = "4 nodes in the hidden layer"),
    custom = TRUE
  )

plot_list$nn10 <- nn(
  simdat,
  rvar = "y",
  evar = "x",

  size = 10,
  decay = 0,

  )
